AGI&nbsp; - "Our organization, our decision-making and funding are designed for the world of yesterday, pre-Covid, pre-Ukraine, pre-conflagration in the Middle East, pre-return of rivalry among great powers. We need a European Union that is up to the world today and tomorrow. So what I propose in the report which the President of the Commission has asked me to prepare is a radical change. That is what is necessary." The former president of the BCE, Mario Draghi, said this, taking part in an event on the European social pillar in La Hulpe, Belgium. "We must achieve a transformation of the European economy, we must be able to rely on a reliable decarbonized energy system, European integrated defence, domestic production in the most innovative sectors and a leading position in technology production," he added.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The former President of the Council noted that "we rightly have an ambitious climate agenda in Europe and rigid targets for electric vehicles, but in a world where our rivals control many of the resources we need, this agenda must be combined with a plan to ensure our supply chain, from critical minerals, batteries, charging infrastructure." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
And again: "We haven't had an industrial deal at European level, despite the Commission's efforts to fill this gap. Despite the positive initiatives in progress, we still lack an overall strategy to respond in these strategies. We invest less than US and China in digital and advanced technologies, including defense. There are only four European top players among the top 50 global companies."
&nbsp;
"We lack a strategy on how to protect our traditional industries from unjust competitiveness due to asymmetries in rules, subsidies and commercial policies," continued Draghi. "The energy industries are a case of study: In other regions these industries not only deal with lower energy prices but also lower regulatory weight and in some cases receive massive subsidies which directly threaten the ability of European companies to compete. Without political actions studied and coordinated it is logical that some of our industries will turn off their capabilities and delocalize outside the EU." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the opinion of the former Italian premier "Once we identify public goods, we must also give ourselves the tools to finance them. The public sector has an important role and in the past I have talked about how we can better use the common debt capacity of the European Union, especially for defence where fragmentation of expenditure reduces our total effectiveness. But most of the investment gap must be covered by private investment.&nbsp; In the EU a very high rate of private savings are mostly channelled into bank deposits and do not finance growth as they should in a larger capital market. This is the reason - it has concluded Draghi - for which to advance in the Union of capital markets is an essential part in the overall strategy of competitiveness". &nbsp;
&nbsp;

